Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

If DNA sample has not been taken from the defendant, the Court orders sample to be taken;  and it may be expunged under 165.77(4) Wis. Statutes. Defendant to comply with I.D. Processing. Defendant to have no contact with victim A listed in the Criminal Complaint/Victim Identification Key.  Defendant is not to share, reproduce or distribute any personal and/or identifying information about the crime victim(s), except to their attorney. Absolute sobriety, defendant is not to possess or consume any alcohol. Defendant is not to use/possess any controlled substances without a valid prescription and take as prescribed. Defendant not to possess any drug paraphernalia. Court orders a protective order pursuant to 940.47 for Victim A listed in the Victim Identification Key.  Court further orders the protective order to be sealed. Defendant to comply with GPS monitoring through Wisconsin Community Services.   Defendant is not to come within 1 mile of Victim A, listed in the Victim Identification Key, or their residence, employment, school or anywhere they frequent.  Defendant to pay costs associated with GPS monitoring. Defendant to be released during regular business hours only and is to report directly to Wisconsin Community Services upon release. Defendant is not to possess any dangerous weapons/firearms. Defendant is not to operate a motor vehicle unless properly licensed. Comply with all licensing restrictions.

3:35 PM District Attorney's Office Law Intern appeared for the State of Wisconsin by Jack Rieder. Defendant David M Barnett in court, in custody.  Attorney Ricardo Tapia in court for David M Barnett. 

Defense acknowledges receipt of complaint and waives reading of complaint. 
Service admitted/advised of charges and potential penalties. 
Court advises of right to an attorney. Defendant is eligible for State Public Defender representation.  An attorney will be appointed. 
PRELIMINARY HEARING REQUESTED WITHIN 20 DAYS. 
The Defendant requests Huber Bailee Status.
The Court denies the request and the issue can be taken up with the Trial Court.
Preliminary hearing scheduled for November 7, 2022 at 10:15 am.
